article.headline: Catchings injured in loss
article.linkText: Sting limit Fever to franchise low in points
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Nothing went right for Indiana on Friday.

Tammy Sutton-Brown had 16 points and seven rebounds as the
Charlotte Sting held the Fever to a franchise-low 41 points in a
63-41 win.

The Fever also lost their top scorer, Tamika Catchings, to a
concussion. Catchings had 15 points and eight rebounds for the
Fever (1-2), but was injured with 2:10 left when she was hit in the
face by Allison Feasters forearm in a rebounding scrum.

A team spokesman said Catchings suffered a mild concussion, but
was going to return to the hotel with the team. Her status for
Tuesday's game at San Antonio is uncertain.

"We'll find out more tomorrow, but she took a pretty good knock
in the face," Indiana coach Brian Winters said. "Hopefully it is
nothing serious and she'll be fine."

No other player scored in double figures for the Fever, whose
previous franchise-low was 45 points against Houston in 2002. Their
12 points in the second half shattered their previous low of 18
against Seattle last season.

Indiana shot 27 percent, third worst in team history, as it lost
its second straight game.

"We forced Indiana to take some not-so-great shots and we
limited them to one shot," Charlotte coach Trudi Lacey said. "It
was a great team effort."

Sutton-Brown dominated the inside and made 10 of 11 free throws
as the Sting (2-1) won their second straight game.

"There was success on the inside so we kept attacking it,"
Sutton-Brown said. "I've tried to improve (on free throw shooting)
and I've had good success so far this year."

The Fever cut a six-point halftime deficit to 35-34 on Natalie
Williams' layup with 18:19 left. But Sutton-Brown's 3-point play
ignited an 20-2 run, capped off by Tynesha Lewis jumper, to make it
55-36 with 6:57 to go.

Indiana was held without a point for more than six minutes
during the decisive run.

"We started the second half pretty well, but then we hit a
drought where we just couldn't hit a shot," Winters said. "We're
going to have to get better, but I credit their defense. They made
us work for shots."

Kelly Miller, playing against Charlotte for the first time since
she was traded by the Sting in the offseason, made her first two
shots, but then missed 10 of her last 11. She finished with seven
points.

The Fever, who are 0-7 all-time in Charlotte, have lost their
last two games in the city by a combined 52 points.
